name: La Barranca
description:
A beautiful and deep canyon with numerous dark, cavern-like sections and fun waterfall rappels, having many fun jumps and one really great slide. The narrows section takes many hours to go through.

This canyon is frequently done in its entirety, with leaving a shuttle car at the Puente de Dios tourist attraction at the bottom. There is also trail access DCR about 1/4 of the way down the technical section (where a concrete footbridge crosses the gorge), so the canyon can be broken into two sections (these are 1 and 2 on the side profiles). However, the upper technical section only takes about 2.25 hours to do (plus approach/exit hiking), so it can be a short day without doing the whole thing.

Additionally, there is an alternate approach named La Escondida (The Hidden), that adds a 45m rappel. If you are only doing the upper section of this canyon you may want to try this approach to add more to the day.

Be sure to read the Queretaro region notes for more information on the area.

Approach

You can drive out to the upper parking area marked on the map, which is a mile down a narrow rough rock road right next to some local houses. Or, you can park in the bus "station" in Pinal de Amoles, and walk the additional mile (or even walk straight from your accommodations if staying in Pinal). From the main parking spot, drop down towards the canyon on the obvious trail along the rocky wall.

Note that this trail bypasses R1 on the section 1 side profile. It's not clear how to drop in above that rappel using the current .kml.

To approach just section 2, take the midpoint trail indicated on the map. This is also the exit if you are just doing section 1. It takes about 45min to walk down, or 1.5hr to walk up this trail.

Descent

The drops are mostly well bolted, although we encountered several places where rappels were indicated on the side profile, but there were no bolts at all, just smooth rock. In all of these cases, we were able to combine the drop with the anchors from the drop immediately above into a two-stage rappel, with the rope we had with us (200'). Also, in section 2 there was a drop that needed new webbing -- only old decayed webbing was found in the watercourse so we replaced it on a nearby tree.

Exit

The canyon eventually opens up and you reach cow paths and manure, and rock-hop for a while, occasionally on big house side rocks you'll need to work your way through. Continue until you reach Puente de Dios, where the river goes through a natural travertine tunnel. This is beautiful but often thronged with tourists. From here you can take off wetsuits and it's a well-built trail for 1mi through a beautiful canyon to the trailhead and your beverage/snack of choice. There are also some deep pools near the bottom of this where the trail becomes a constructed concrete walkway along the canyon wall, that might be fun to jump into.

At one point after reaching the cow paths, and before Puente de Dios, you'll encounter a big water pipe on LDC and you might be tempted to try to use the trail next to it, but it is not clear where it leads and downstream the hillside turns into cliffs, so not sure if it's possible to use that path to bypass any of the rock hopping in the canyon bottom.

If just doing section 1, exit RDC at the concrete footbridge, and hike about 1.5hrs up a well-established livestock trail to the road. At a junction you will reach the approach trail; take it the rest of the way up. It is easiest to cross the rocky wall at this junction by climbing up the hillside for 100m or so.

Red tape

They'll probably catch you as you exit through the Puente de Dios entrance point. The fee was 120 pesos per person in Apr 2021, and again Feb 2022. Parking here is 70 pesos per vehicle.
